Intersection of Two Linked Lists — Brief Note

Idea:
Two pointers walk through both lists.
When a pointer reaches the end of its list, it moves to the head of the other list.
This makes both pointers travel the same total distance.

If lists share a common tail → both pointers will eventually stand on the same node → intersection.
If they don’t share → both pointers become null at the same time → no intersection.

Intersection is based on:
✔ Same node (same memory)
✘ Not “same value”
Time Complexity:
👉 O(m + n)
Because each pointer scans list A + list B once.
Space Complexity:
👉 O(1)
Only two pointers used.



public class Solution {
    public ListNode getIntersectionNode(ListNode headA, ListNode headB) {
        if(headA==null|| headB==null) return null;
        ListNode a=headA;
        ListNode b=headB;
        while(a!=b){
            a=(a==null)?headB:a.next;
            b=(b==null)?headA:b.next;
        }
        return b;
        
    }
}



